# Comprehensive GPO hardening with explanations

All paths are under **Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates** unless noted.

## Note on Windows Error Reporting

WER (service: **WerSvc**) catches crashes, writes local dumps, and optionally uploads to Microsoft. Disable the upload, keep the service — you'll still get local crash diagnostics.

---

## 1. Data Collection and telemetry core

Path: **Windows Components → Data Collection and Preview Builds**

- **Allow Diagnostic Data** → Enabled, "Diagnostic data off" (Enterprise) or "Send required diagnostic data" (Pro)
  - Stops the DiagTrack service from collecting and uploading app usage, feature telemetry, and performance data to Microsoft on a timer
- **Do not show feedback notifications** → Enabled
  - Stops "How do you feel about Windows?" popups
- **Disable pre-release features or settings** → Enabled
  - Stops the machine from opting into experimental A/B tests Microsoft runs silently
- **Toggle user control over Insider builds** → Disabled
  - Prevents users from joining the Insider program and pulling preview builds
- **Limit Diagnostic Log Collection** → Enabled
  - Restricts the extra log bundles telemetry collects beyond the baseline
- **Limit Dump Collection** → Enabled
  - Stops auto-upload of full memory dumps to Microsoft
- **Configure telemetry opt-in setting user interface** → Enabled, "Disable telemetry opt-in Settings"
  - Hides the Settings UI so users can't turn telemetry back on
- **Allow device name to be sent in Windows diagnostic data** → Disabled
  - Strips hostname from anything that does leak out

## 2. Windows Error Reporting

Path: **Windows Components → Windows Error Reporting**

- **Disable Windows Error Reporting** → Disabled (counterintuitive — "Disabled" here keeps WER available)
  - Keeps crash dumps writing locally to `%LOCALAPPDATA%\CrashDumps` and Event Log for your own troubleshooting
- **Do not send additional data** → Enabled
  - Blocks the second-stage upload where WER asks to send extra files
- **Send data when connected to a restricted/cost network** → Disabled
  - Prevents upload on metered connections
- **Automatically send memory dumps for OS-generated error reports** → Disabled
  - Stops silent upload of kernel dumps

Path: **Windows Components → Windows Error Reporting → Consent**

- **Configure Default consent** → Enabled, "Always ask before sending data"
  - Forces a prompt instead of silent upload

## 3. Internet Communication settings (catch-all)

Path: **System → Internet Communication Management → Internet Communication settings**

- **Turn off Windows Network Connectivity Status Indicator active tests** → Enabled
  - Stops the constant ping to `msftconnecttest.com` that Windows uses to draw the tray internet icon — big chatter reduction
- **Turn off Windows Customer Experience Improvement Program** → Enabled
  - Disables the legacy CEIP data channel (separate from modern telemetry)
- **Turn off Search Companion content file updates** → Enabled
  - Stops periodic download of search assistant data
- **Turn off handwriting recognition error reporting** → Enabled
  - Handwriting subsystem stops phoning home
- **Turn off handwriting personalization data sharing** → Enabled
  - Stops upload of your handwriting samples for "improvement"
- **Turn off printing over HTTP** → Enabled
  - Disables IPP outbound traffic for printers you don't use that way
- **Turn off downloading of print drivers over HTTP** → Enabled
  - Blocks driver downloads from Microsoft's HTTP driver server
- **Turn off the "Publish to Web" task for files and folders** → Enabled
  - Removes the Explorer option that would upload files to a web service
- **Turn off Internet download for Web publishing and online ordering wizards** → Enabled
  - Disables the provider list download these wizards use
- **Turn off Internet File Association service** → Enabled
  - Stops Windows from asking Microsoft online "what app opens this extension I don't know"
- **Turn off Internet Connection Wizard if URL refers to Microsoft.com** → Enabled
  - Blocks the ICW from calling Microsoft during setup
- **Turn off Registration if URL refers to Microsoft.com** → Enabled
  - Blocks the old product registration ping
- **Turn off Event Viewer "Events.asp" links** → Enabled
  - Removes the "More information" link in Event Viewer that fetches from Microsoft
- **Turn off Help and Support Center "Did you know?" content** → Enabled
  - Stops help content from being refreshed online
- **Turn off Help and Support Center Microsoft Knowledge Base search** → Enabled
  - Disables the online KB search in help
- **Turn off Automatic Root Certificates Update** → Enabled (with caution)
  - Stops automatic download of new root CA certs — warning: can break TLS to sites with newer roots if you don't manage certs manually

## 4. Cloud Content / ads / Start menu suggestions

Path: **Windows Components → Cloud Content**

- **Turn off Microsoft consumer experiences** → Enabled
  - Stops Windows from installing "suggested" apps (Candy Crush, Spotify, etc.) and showing Start menu promotions
- **Turn off cloud consumer account state content** → Enabled
  - Blocks personalized content fetched based on your MSA
- **Turn off cloud optimized content** → Enabled
  - Stops the dynamic content downloads that rotate through Windows
- **Do not show Windows tips** → Enabled
  - Kills the "tip of the day" popups that fetch content online
- **Do not suggest third-party content in Windows spotlight** → Enabled
  - Stops third-party promos from appearing on lock screen
- **Turn off Windows Spotlight on lock screen** → Enabled
  - Disables the rotating Bing images that pull fresh content daily
- **Turn off Windows Spotlight features** → Enabled
  - Kills Spotlight across the whole OS, not just lock screen
- **Turn off Windows Spotlight on Settings** → Enabled
  - Removes the suggestion cards that appear in Settings

## 5. Search / Cortana

Path: **Windows Components → Search**

- **Allow Cortana** → Disabled
  - Turns off Cortana entirely — stops voice processing, personalization pings, and the whole Cortana background stack
- **Allow Cortana above lock screen** → Disabled
  - Extra layer blocking Cortana from the lock screen
- **Allow search and Cortana to use location** → Disabled
  - Stops search from using GPS/Wi-Fi positioning for results
- **Don't search the web or display web results in Search** → Enabled
  - This is the big one — every keystroke in the Start menu currently hits Bing. This stops that
- **Set what information is shared in Search** → Enabled, "Anonymous info"
  - Reduces data sent with any remaining searches
- **Allow Cloud Search** → Disabled
  - Stops searching across cloud services (OneDrive, Outlook) when you use local search
- **Allow indexing of encrypted files** → Disabled
  - Security hygiene, not traffic-related

## 6. Edge Update service

Path: **Microsoft Edge Update → Applications** (requires MSEdgeUpdate ADMX)

- **Update policy override default** → Enabled, "Updates disabled"
  - Stops the Edge updater service from reaching out every few hours to check for new versions

Path: **Microsoft Edge Update → Applications → Microsoft Edge**

- **Update policy override** → Enabled, "Updates disabled"
  - Same, specifically for the Edge browser app

Path: **Microsoft Edge Update → Preferences**

- **Auto-update check period override** → Enabled, 0 minutes
  - Sets the check interval to zero, which means "never"

## 7. Edge browser

Path: **Microsoft Edge**

- **Configure Edge startup boost** → Disabled
  - Stops Edge from pre-launching hidden processes at logon to "feel fast" when you click the icon
- **Continue running background apps after Microsoft Edge closes** → Disabled
  - When you close Edge, it actually closes — no lingering helper processes
- **Enable browser background mode** → Disabled
  - Same idea, different setting — kills the background service that handles notifications after close
- **Automatically send diagnostic data** → Disabled
  - Stops Edge's built-in telemetry uploads
- **Send site information to improve Microsoft services** → Disabled
  - Stops URL/site data from being sent for "service improvement"
- **Allow personalization of ads, search, and news by sending browsing history to Microsoft** → Disabled
  - Stops Edge from shipping your browsing history to Microsoft for ad targeting
- **Enable experimentation** → Disabled
  - Opts out of the A/B tests Edge runs silently
- **Configure Do Not Track** → Enabled
  - Sends DNT header with web requests (weak but free)
- **Enable network prediction** → Disabled
  - Stops Edge from speculatively opening TCP connections and DNS lookups for sites it guesses you'll visit
- **Allow suggestions from local providers on blank pages** → Disabled
  - No auto-content on new tab page
- **Enable search suggestions** → Disabled
  - Stops every address bar keystroke from hitting Bing for autocomplete
- **Show recommendations in the Edge menu** → Disabled
  - Removes promoted content in the hamburger menu
- **Hide the First-run experience and splash screen** → Enabled
  - Skips the "welcome" setup flow that makes online calls
- **Configure Edge Discover** → Disabled
  - Kills the Discover sidebar (fetches content continuously)
- **Configure Shopping in Microsoft Edge** → Disabled
  - Disables the shopping/coupon feature that scans pages and calls out
- **Enable Follow service in Microsoft Edge** → Disabled
  - Stops the feed-following service that polls for updates

## 8. Chrome Update service

Path: **Google → Google Update → Applications** (requires Chrome ADMX)

- **Update policy override default** → Enabled, "Updates disabled"
  - Stops GoogleUpdate.exe from background update checks

Path: **Google → Google Update → Applications → Google Chrome**

- **Update policy override** → Enabled, "Updates disabled"
  - Same, for Chrome specifically

Path: **Google → Google Update → Preferences**

- **Auto-update check period override** → Enabled, 0 minutes
  - Sets update check interval to never

## 9. Chrome browser

Path: **Google → Google Chrome**

- **Continue running background apps when Google Chrome is closed** → Disabled
  - Closes Chrome processes when you close the window — no background extensions, no persistent helpers
- **Enables or disables metrics reporting** → Disabled
  - Stops Chrome's UMA telemetry uploads
- **Enable network prediction** → Enabled, "Do not predict actions on any network connection"
  - Stops preconnect, DNS prefetch, and speculative resource loading
- **Enable search suggestions** → Disabled
  - Omnibox keystrokes no longer hit Google for autocomplete
- **Enable URL-keyed anonymized data collection** → Disabled
  - Stops Chrome from uploading URLs you visit for feature improvement
- **Enable or disable spell checking web service** → Disabled
  - Stops Chrome's enhanced spell check (sends text to Google) — falls back to local
- **Allow user feedback** → Disabled
  - Removes the "Report an issue" feature that uploads data
- **Enable Safe Browsing** → Your call
  - Disabling stops reputation pings on every download/URL, but you lose malware protection

## 10. OneDrive

Path: **Windows Components → OneDrive**

- **Prevent the usage of OneDrive for file storage** → Enabled
  - Blocks OneDrive client from running at all — stops the sync daemon, login attempts, and folder scanning
- **Prevent OneDrive from generating network traffic until the user signs in** → Enabled
  - If you don't fully disable, at least stops OneDrive from chattering before login

## 11. Microsoft Store

Path: **Windows Components → Store**

- **Turn off Automatic Download and Install of updates** → Enabled
  - Stops the Store service from polling for app updates in the background
- **Turn off the offer to update to the latest version of Windows** → Enabled
  - Stops the "Windows 11 is available" kind of upsell checks

## 12. Location services

Path: **Windows Components → Location and Sensors**

- **Turn off location** → Enabled
  - Disables the Windows Location Service, which otherwise keeps a warm Wi-Fi/cellular scan running for fast fixes
- **Turn off location scripting** → Enabled
  - Blocks script access to location
- **Turn off sensors** → Enabled
  - Kills the sensor framework entirely if you don't need it

Path: **Windows Components → Location and Sensors → Windows Location Provider**

- **Turn off Windows Location Provider** → Enabled
  - Stops the provider that talks to Microsoft's location API

## 13. Maps

Path: **Windows Components → Maps**

- **Turn off Automatic Download and Update of Map Data** → Enabled
  - Maps app won't pull regional map tiles in the background
- **Turn off unsolicited network traffic on the Offline Maps settings page** → Enabled
  - Offline Maps page itself won't phone home when you open it

## 14. Speech / typing / inking

Path: **Control Panel → Regional and Language Options**

- **Allow users to enable online speech recognition services** → Disabled
  - Stops cloud speech recognition; forces local-only

Path: **Windows Components → Speech**

- **Allow Automatic Update of Speech Data** → Disabled
  - Language/voice model files don't sync in the background

Path: **Windows Components → Text Input**

- **Improve inking and typing recognition** → Disabled
  - Stops upload of handwriting/typing samples to train Microsoft's models

## 15. Delivery Optimization

Path: **Windows Components → Delivery Optimization**

- **Download Mode** → Enabled, "HTTP only" (99) or "Bypass" (100)
  - Stops your machine from participating in peer-to-peer Windows Update sharing — no uploading update chunks to strangers, no seeding to other PCs

## 16. Windows Update

Path: **Windows Components → Windows Update → Manage end user experience**

- **Configure Automatic Updates** → Enabled, "Notify for download and auto install"
  - You control when updates download instead of Windows doing it whenever

Path: **Windows Components → Windows Update → Manage updates offered from Windows Update**

- **Do not include drivers with Windows Updates** → Enabled
  - Skips driver downloads through WU (you'll manage drivers separately)

## 17. Game DVR / Xbox background

Path: **Windows Components → Windows Game Recording and Broadcasting**

- **Enables or disables Windows Game Recording and Broadcasting** → Disabled
  - Stops Game DVR's background recording service and the Xbox-connected chatter

## 18. News and interests / Widgets

Path: **Windows Components → News and interests**

- **Enable news and interests on the taskbar** → Disabled
  - Removes the taskbar widget that constantly fetches news/weather

Path: **Windows Components → Widgets**

- **Allow widgets** → Disabled
  - Kills the Widgets board in Windows 11 (a continuous content feed)

## 19. Push notifications

Path: **Windows Components → Push Notifications**

- **Turn off notifications network usage** → Enabled
  - Stops WNS (Windows Notification Service) from maintaining an open connection to Microsoft for app notifications
- **Turn off tile notifications** → Enabled
  - Stops live tile updates that pull content

## 20. Sync your settings

Path: **Windows Components → Sync your settings**

- **Do not sync** → Enabled
  - Stops Windows from syncing themes, passwords, language, etc. to your Microsoft account across devices

## 21. Device driver search

Path: **System → Device Installation**

- **Specify search order for device driver source locations** → Enabled, "Do not search Windows Update"
  - When you plug in hardware, Windows won't reach out to WU for drivers
- **Prevent device metadata retrieval from the Internet** → Enabled
  - Stops Windows from fetching device icons/names from Microsoft when you plug in hardware

## 22. Autoplay

Path: **Windows Components → AutoPlay Policies**

- **Turn off Autoplay** → Enabled, "All drives"
  - Security-focused; prevents autorun when USB/CD is inserted — unrelated to network but good hygiene

## 23. Find My Device

Path: **Windows Components → Find My Device**

- **Turn On/Off Find My Device** → Disabled
  - Stops the service that reports location to Microsoft for device recovery

## 24. RSS feeds / content view

Path: **Windows Components → RSS Feeds**

- **Turn off background synchronization for feeds and Web Slices** → Enabled
  - Stops the Common Feed List from polling subscribed feeds on a timer
- **Prevent automatic discovery of feeds and Web Slices** → Enabled
  - Stops IE/Explorer from probing pages for feeds

## 25. Font download

Path: **Network → Fonts**

- **Enable Font Providers** → Disabled
  - Stops Windows from downloading additional fonts on-demand from Microsoft's font service

## 26. IPv6 transition technologies (optional)

Path: **Network → TCPIP Settings → IPv6 Transition Technologies**

- **Set Teredo State** → Enabled, "Disabled State"
  - Disables Teredo tunneling (NAT traversal for IPv6 over IPv4); it maintains an open UDP tunnel to a Microsoft relay
- **Set 6to4 State** → Enabled, "Disabled State"
  - Disables 6to4 transitional tunneling
- **Set ISATAP State** → Enabled, "Disabled State"
  - Disables ISATAP — only relevant in specific enterprise IPv6 scenarios

Only apply these if you're fully IPv4 or native IPv6 — Teredo especially opens a background tunnel you probably don't want.

---

## Order of operations

Load required ADMX files into `C:\Windows\PolicyDefinitions` first (Windows 11 ADMX, Edge, Edge Update, Chrome, Chrome Update, OneDrive). Apply in batches, reboot between, and verify with `gpresult /h report.html`. Watch the result with Task Manager and `Get-NetTCPConnection` at idle — you should see a dramatic drop in background processes and outbound connections.
